# CaptionDB Frontend Engineering Contract

## Purpose

This document defines the mandatory frontend engineering standards for CaptionDB.

The frontend is responsible for presenting information and interacting with users.

It must never contain business logic, AI processing, or infrastructure logic.

The frontend should remain lightweight, predictable, modular, and maintainable.

---

# Frontend Philosophy

The frontend is a presentation layer.

It is NOT responsible for:

- AI processing
- Video processing
- OCR
- Scene detection
- Caption generation
- Fireworks API
- Export generation

Those belong to the backend.

The frontend only displays state and sends user actions.

---

# Technology Stack

Mandatory technologies:

- React
- TypeScript
- Vite

Optional (if justified):

- React Query
- Zustand
- React Hook Form
- Zod

Do not introduce dependencies without justification.

---

# Folder Structure

Frontend should follow a feature-based architecture.

frontend/

src/

components/

features/

hooks/

services/

api/

types/

utils/

constants/

assets/

styles/

contexts/

pages/

layouts/

providers/

tests/

Keep responsibilities isolated.

---

# Component Philosophy

Components should be:

Small

Reusable

Focused

Predictable

Avoid large components.

Split responsibilities early.

---

# Component Responsibilities

Components should:

Render UI

Handle user interaction

Receive props

Trigger callbacks

Never:

Call Fireworks

Contain AI logic

Perform OCR

Perform video processing

Contain backend business logic

---

# Smart vs Presentational Components

Prefer presentational components.

Business logic belongs in:

Hooks

Services

State management

Never inside rendering logic.

---

# State Management

Use local state for local UI.

Use global state only for shared application state.

Avoid prop drilling.

Global state should remain minimal.

---

# API Communication

All API communication must go through:

services/api/

Never call fetch() directly from components.

Never duplicate HTTP logic.

Create reusable API clients.

---

# API Layer

The API layer should:

Handle requests

Handle responses

Handle retries

Handle errors

Handle authentication (future)

Components should never know implementation details.

---

# Type Safety

Every response should have a TypeScript interface.

Never use any.

Prefer explicit interfaces.

Avoid unknown unless justified.

---

# Constants

Never hardcode:

Endpoints

Routes

Labels

Prompt names

Feature flags

Export formats

Theme values

Configuration belongs in constants or configuration files.

---

# Forms

Use controlled forms.

Validate input before submission.

Display user-friendly validation messages.

Never trust client input.

Backend validates everything again.

---

# Error Handling

Every API request should gracefully handle:

Network failures

Timeouts

Server errors

Validation errors

Unexpected responses

Never leave the UI hanging.

Always inform the user.

---

# Loading States

Every asynchronous operation must display:

Loading indicator

Disabled actions when appropriate

Progress when available

Never leave users wondering.

---

# Empty States

Design explicit empty states.

Examples:

No projects

No videos

No captions

No search results

Provide guidance instead of blank screens.

---

# Optimistic Updates

Use optimistic updates only when safe.

Rollback changes if requests fail.

Never mislead the user.

---

# Component Naming

Use PascalCase.

Examples

VideoUploader

ProjectSidebar

CaptionCard

ExportDialog

---

# Hooks

Custom hooks begin with:

use

Examples

useProjects

useCaptions

useVideoUpload

useProcessingStatus

Hooks should encapsulate reusable logic.

---

# Styling

Maintain consistent styling.

Avoid inline styles unless necessary.

Use reusable design tokens.

Keep visual consistency across the application.

---

# Accessibility

Every interactive component should support:

Keyboard navigation

Focus management

ARIA labels where appropriate

Semantic HTML

Readable contrast

Accessibility is mandatory.

---

# Performance

Avoid unnecessary renders.

Memoize expensive computations when justified.

Lazy load heavy components.

Split code where beneficial.

Do not optimize prematurely.

Measure first.

---

# File Uploads

Validate selected files before upload.

Show file information.

Display upload progress.

Reject unsupported formats immediately.

Never trust filenames.

---

# Notifications

Use consistent notifications for:

Success

Warning

Error

Information

Messages should be concise and actionable.

---

# Dialogs

Dialogs should:

Trap focus

Support keyboard dismissal

Prevent accidental destructive actions

Request confirmation when necessary.

---

# Routing

Separate routing from page implementation.

Avoid embedding business logic inside routes.

Protect future authenticated routes.

---

# Search

Debounce search requests.

Avoid sending unnecessary API calls.

Cache previous results when appropriate.

---

# React Best Practices

Prefer functional components.

Prefer hooks.

Avoid class components.

Keep render methods simple.

Avoid deeply nested JSX.

Extract reusable UI.

---

# Testing

Frontend components should support:

Unit tests

Interaction tests

Accessibility tests

Integration tests

Avoid tightly coupling components to backend implementation.

---

# Documentation

Document reusable components.

Document custom hooks.

Document API services.

Document complex UI behavior.

---

# Security

Escape user-generated content.

Never render unsafe HTML.

Never expose secrets.

Never trust browser validation.

Sanitize displayed data where appropriate.

---

# Future Compatibility

Design components for future expansion.

Support:

Additional caption styles

Additional export formats

Authentication

Collaboration

Real-time updates

History

Versioning

---

# Code Review Checklist

Before completing frontend implementation verify:

✓ Component has one responsibility

✓ No business logic inside UI

✓ Strong typing

✓ API through service layer

✓ Proper loading state

✓ Proper error state

✓ Proper empty state

✓ Accessibility considered

✓ No duplicated components

✓ No hardcoded configuration

✓ Performance reviewed

✓ Security reviewed

✓ Documentation updated

✓ Tests added

If any check fails, revise implementation before completion.

---

End of Frontend Engineering Contract.
